{{Redirect|Animal art|the decoration of objects with animal motifs|Animal style|artwork created by non-humans|Animal-made art}} [[Image:Whistlejacket by George Stubbs edit.jpg|thumb|240px|[[George Stubbs]] (1724-1806): ''[[Whistlejacket]]'' (c. 1762), [[National Gallery]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/paintings/george-stubbs-whistlejacket |title=Whistlejacket: about 1762, George Stubbs |publisher=[[National Gallery]] |accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref>]]
An '''animal painter''' is an artist who specialises in (or is known for their skill in) the portrayal of animals.
The ''[[Oxford English Dictionary|OED]]'' dates the first express use of the term "animal painter" to the mid-18th century: by English [[physician]], [[Natural history|naturalist]] and writer [[John Berkenhout]] (1726-1791).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/animal-painting |title=Animal painting |publisher=''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' |accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref> From the early 20th century, ''wildlife artist'' became a more usual term for contemporary animal painters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldlandtrust.org/gallery/exhibitions/wildlife-art-20th-century |title=Wildlife Art of the 20th Century |publisher=[[Woodland Trust]] |accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref>
==History== Especially in the 17th century, animal painters would often collaborate with other artists, who would either paint the main subject in a [[history painting|historical]] or mythological piece, or the [[Landscape painting|landscape]] background in a decorative one. [[Frans Snyders]], a founder of the Baroque animal painting tradition, often provided the animals, and also still lifes of food, for [[Peter Paul Rubens]]; a different landscape specialist might provide the background.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Frans-Snyders |title=Frans Snyders |publisher=''[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]'' |accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref>
In the [[Dutch Golden Age]] such specialists tended to produce smaller genre paintings concentrating on their specialism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/gnrn/hd_gnrn.htm |title=Frans Snyders |publisher=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] |accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref> Animal painters came lower down in the [[hierarchy of genres]], but the best painters could make a very good living; many royal and aristocratic patrons were more interested in their subject matter than that of the more prestigious genres. Mainly in England, there were still more specialised painters from the 18th century who produced portraits of racehorses and prize specimens of livestock,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/art/art-features/10429771/Why-the-George-Stubbs-paintings-were-worth-saving.html |title=Why the George Stubbs paintings were worth saving |publisher=''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' |accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref> whereas in France animal subjects continued to be decorative [[Capriccio (painting)|capriccios]] often set around garden statuary.
In 2014 ''[[The Guardian]]'' nominated ''[[The Goldfinch (painting)|The Goldfinch]]'' (1654) by [[Carel Fabritius]] (1622-1654) as the finest animal portrait.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/jonathanjonesblog/2014/jun/27/top-10-animal-portraits-in-art |title=The top 10 animal portraits in art |publisher=''[[The Guardian]]'' |accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>
==Animalier== [[Animalier]], as a collective plural noun, is a term used in [[antiques]] for small-scale sculptures of animals in particular (animalier bronzes), but also paintings of animals. Large numbers of these were produced - often mass-produced - in the 19th century in France and elsewhere. Many earlier examples can be found, but [[animalier]] sculpture became more popular, and reputable, in early 19th century Paris, with the works of [[Antoine-Louis Barye]] (1795-1875) - for whom the term was coined, decisively, by critics in 1831<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O110845/walking-lion-statuette-barye-antoine-louis/ |title=Walking lion |publisher=[[Victoria and Albert Museum]] |accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref> - and [[Christopher Fratin]] (1801-1864).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/luxury/collectables/30507/rise-of-the-animal-sculptures.html |title=Rise of the animal sculptures |publisher=''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' |accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref> By the mid 19th-century, a taste for animal subjects was widespread among the middle-classes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O171334/an-indian-panther-lying-down-statuette-barbedienne-ferdinand/ |title=An Indian panther lying down |publisher=[[Victoria and Albert Museum]] |accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref>
==Wildlife conservation== Many modern wildlife artists or art groups hold benefits to support [[wildlife conservation]], or participate in contests held by wildlife conservation organisations.<ref>{{cite web |title=About the AFC |url=http://www.natureartists.com/ |publisher=Artists for Conservation |accessdate=9 July 2016}}</ref>
