__notoc__ {{More footnotes|date=February 2011}} The '''Cinema of Transgression''' is a term coined by [[Nick Zedd]] in 1985 to describe a [[New York City]]-based [[underground film]] movement, consisting of a loose-knit group of like-minded artists using [[shock value]] and [[humor]] in their work.<ref>{{cite book | title=Punk Rock: So What?: The Cultural Legacy of Punk | publisher=Routledge | last1=Sabin |first1=Roger | year=2002 | pages=69–72 | isbn=9780203448403 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u1cDUc9_LC4C&pg=PA69#v=onepage}}</ref> Key players in this movement were Zedd, [[Kembra Pfahler]], [[John Waters]], [[Tessa Hughes-Freeland]], [[Casandra Stark]], [[Beth B]], Tommy Turner, [[Richard Kern]], and [[Lydia Lunch]], who in the late 1970s and mid-1980s began to make [[no budget film|very low-budget films]] using cheap 8&nbsp;mm cameras.
Zedd outlined his [[philosophy]] on the Cinema of Transgression in "The Cinema of Transgression Manifesto", published under the name Orion Jeriko in the [[zine]] ''[[The Underground Film Bulletin]]'' (1984–90).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://feastofhateandfear.com/archives/zedd.html |title=The Cinema of Transgression Manifesto |last1=Zedd |first1=Nick |date=1985 |website= |publisher= |accessdate=7 June 2014}}</ref>
Cinema of Transgression continues to heavily influence underground filmmakers. In 2000, the [[British Film Institute]] showed a retrospective of the movement's work introduced by those involved in the production of the original video films.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b83db7f51 | title=The Cinema of Transgression 1984–90. |last1=Zedd |first1=Nick |date=2000 |website= |publisher= |accessdate=}}</ref>
In November 2001, reclusive British filmmaker [[Philip Goring]] passionately read the original [[manifesto]] written by Nick Zedd, from dawn to dusk, at [[Speakers' Corner]], Hyde Park, London, a long-standing haven of free speech where many of the world's great thinkers and activists have addressed the public.
