{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Matisse518.jpg | backcolor=#FBF5DF | painting_alignment=right | image_size=300px | title=Still Life with Geraniums | artist=[[Henri Matisse]] | year=1910 | medium=[[oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric=180 | width_metric=220 | height_imperial=70.9 | width_imperial=86.6 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Munich, Germany]] | museum=[[Pinakothek der Moderne]] }}
'''''Still Life with Geraniums''''' is a 1910 oil on canvas painting by [[Henri Matisse]].
The oil painting is in the collection of [[Pinakothek der Moderne]], [[Munich, Germany]], to whom it was given in 1912, thus becoming, according to the museum, the first Matisse to enter a public collection.<ref name=nyt-pin>Butler, Desmond. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B07E2D8133EF933A25752C1A9649C8B63 "Art/Architecture; A Home for the Modern In a Time-Bound City"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', 10 November 2002. Retrieved 25 December 2007.</ref> ''Still Life with Geraniums'' was one of six paintings in the museum's collection to survive [[World War II]].<ref name=nyt-pin/>
This particular painting should not be confused with Matisse's earlier 1906 painting ''Still Life with a Geranium'', which is held by the [[Art Institute of Chicago]],<ref>[http://206.13.35.3/press/pressroom.asp?do=images&id=305 SFMOMA presents Matisse: Painter as Sculptor]{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}, [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art|SFMOMA]] press release, 12 April 2007</ref> or his 1912 painting ''Pot of Geraniums'' in the [[National Gallery of Art]].<ref>[http://www.art-si.org/PDFs/Acquisition/CIC03_Berns.pdf "Spectral Imaging of Matisse’s Pot of Geraniums: A Case Study"], art-si.org. Retrieved 26 December 2007.</ref> ([[Juan Gris]] also painted ''Pot of Geraniums'' in 1915, sold at auction in 2007.)<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_kmafp/is_200705/ai_n19097545 "Giacometti, Juan Gris records fall at New York art sales"], AFP, May 2007. Retrieved from findarticles.com, 26 December 2007.</ref>
